    <item>
      <title>What Do Bowflex Home Gym PR1000 Users Have to Say?</title>
      <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~3/JA5J2jxAW9Y/what-do-bowflex-home-gym-pr1000-users.html</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 25 May 2012 15:35:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
<a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-T9fIGHcE4hM/T7-JYrmzgZI/AAAAAAAABoE/0JXNFyzSTlo/s1600/bowflex+pr1000.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-T9fIGHcE4hM/T7-JYrmzgZI/AAAAAAAABoE/0JXNFyzSTlo/s1600/bowflex+pr1000.jpg" /></a></div>
The <b>Bowflex PR1000 Home Gym</b> is a popular, budget priced home gym that lets you do over 30 power building resistance exercises.<br />
<br />
With 210 lbs. of Power Rod resistance rods, it has all the weight most people will ever need to get in a top to bottom, total body workout at home. With this single machine, you can exercise your abs, arms, chest, back, shoulders, and lower body.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001AS697O/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B001AS697O">Find out how you can save up to 44% on a Bowflex PR1000 Home Gym. Order yours today.</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B001AS697O" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /><br />
<br />
You can set up your home gym almost anywhere. A 9 foot by 7 foot is roomy enough to deploy this gym with ease.<br />
<br />
<b>Build muscle and get stronger fast with Bowflex Power Rod technology.&nbsp; </b>You can adjust the amount of resistance from as little a 5 pounds of resistance all the way to 210 lbs. Unlike free weights, power rods give you more even resistance throughout the exercise. They eliminate the inertia and risk of joint pain that can occur using free weights. ( And, you never have to worry about dropping a weight on your toes!)<br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
<i>C.Bayne </i>calls her Bowflex PR1000 home gym,<b> "Great for the price."</b><br />
<br />
<blockquote class="tr_bq">
<i>"I put this together myself, which is a pretty good workout in itself. 
(OK, my husband helped a bit, but I did 90% of it.) It's sturdy, but not
 rock solid.  It's fairly small for a work out machine, and the bench 
can fold up, so the footprint is about 4'x3'.  It's about 6 1/2 feet 
tall.  I'm 5'4" and it's tall enough for me.  My husband is 5'11" and 
this is just barely tall enough for him.  The bars "weight" is 105 lbs 
for each side, which might not be enough for a body builder, but it's 
good for us.  After a half hour work out, my muscles know I've been 
doing something.<br /><br />The booklet that comes with the machine has several exercises, but going out to the web will get you a lot more exercises.<br /><br />This
 is a very good exercise machine for the casual exerciser, as long as 
you're not too tall.  It's easy to use, it doesn't take up too much 
space, and it's not prohibitively expensive.  It's sturdy, and you can 
work out all your muscles"
      </i></blockquote>
<br />
<b>Other features and specs for the PR1000 home gym:</b><br />
<ul>
<li>Want to get your heart going? The sliding seat rail lets you add a calorie blasting aerobic rowing session to your workouts. You can also use it to warm up and cool down before and after your lifting exercises.&nbsp;</li>
<li>The triple function hand grips give you more flexibility with your workouts.&nbsp;</li>
<li>&nbsp;Exercise your legs with curls and extensions. The leg station features four inch upholstered roller cushions for your comfort. </li>
<li>You can do over 30 resistance exercises. These include everything from horizontal, decline, and inclined bench presses to lat pulldowns to tricep exercises to calf raises. See a more complete list <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001AS697O/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B001AS697O">here.</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B001AS697O" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" />&nbsp;</li>
<li>The Bowflex PR1000 gym fold up for easy storage.&nbsp;</li>
<li>The maximum user weight for this home gym is 300 lbs.</li>
</ul>
<b><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001AS697O/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B001AS697O">Order your Bowflex PR1000 Home Gym from Amazon today and save up to 44%.</a></b><br />
<br />
<b>What Bowflex PR1000 users have to say about their home gyms.&nbsp;</b><br />
<br />
;Bowflex PR1000 home gym has been around for several years. Finding out what the women and men who have already purchased and use this gym have to say is insightful and valuable if you are thinking of taking the plunge and buying one yourself.<br />
<br />
We found more than 100 customer reviews on the Bowflex PR1000 home gym at Amazon. These reviewers talked about everything from the time it took to assemble their home gym once it arrived to the sturdiness of the machine to the benefits they derived from using it.<br />
<br />
The overall grade was a very good 4.4 stars out a possible 5 star rating. To be sure, there were some complaints. But the cumulative experience with this home gym was good.<br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
<i>Ellery </i>is a personal trainer from New York. He gives the Bowflex PR1000 home gym a 4 star rating. In his review, Ellery addresses the concern some people raise about only having 210 lbs. of resistance.<br />
<br />
<blockquote class="tr_bq">
<i>"I have been a personal fitness trainer for many years and at first I too
 was a skeptic about the whole resistance rod thing. I have read other 
reviews where people who bought this particular unit say that 210lbs is 
not enough weight to get a good work out.<br /><br />I would suggest to 
those of you who think you need more weight than that to try slowing the
 motion of your reps on whatever exercise you are doing way, way down. 
Say for instance you are doing bicep curls: As you curl up, do so with a
 slow count of 8. At the bottom of the movement start the count at one, 
then SLOWY curl it up to the top of the movement ending on eight, then 
do the same on the way back down to the bottom of the movement to get 
the negative resistance, which makes each single rep more like two reps 
both positive and negative, up then down.<br /><br />This will cause you to 
have to MUSCLE the weight up and down as opposed to using momentum. I 
would also suggest that you try working each muscle group to failure if 
you can handle it. This method can make 20lbs seem like 50 after just 
two sets if you do it correctly. Mind you, you will be so very soar, but
 in a good way and the results will no doubt satisfy"</i></blockquote>
<br />
<i>French</i>, from Idaho Falls, Idaho says he absolutely loves his new home gym. Perhaps the 7 pound weight loss is why.&nbsp; He gave it 4 stars, saying the only drawback was "not enough weight to work the legs". Still, French feels the advantages far outweigh the disadvantages. <br />
<br />
<i>MusicLover</i> from Maine found the PR1000 only adequate. She advises you to try the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001AS4YRQ/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B001AS4YRQ">Bowflex PR3000 Home Gym</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B001AS4YRQ" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /> for more resistance. Here is part of what she had to say.<br />
<br />
<blockquote class="tr_bq">
<i>&nbsp;"The machine itself appears to be of good quality.  And after the first 
workout, I am sore, which is what's to be expected.  But I am an 
overweight, out-of-shape, 50-yr-old woman and even I could Leg Press the
 full weight (210lbs) on my first workout.  And unfortunately, as others
 have observed, you cannot upgrade the PR1000.<br /><br />This seems to me 
to be the second drawback, for which I docked them their second star.  
Coupled with the relatively low maximum weight, I could see the 
inability to upgrade being a big limitation for most men and any strong 
woman who is already in great shape.  If that's you, I would skip this 
machine and spend the money on another model - or plan to supplement it.<br /><br />Since
 I don't come anywhere near to maxing out the weight for any of the 
upper-torso exercises, the machine is still very useful to me.  If my 
upper body is able to max it out in a year or two I will be delighted.  
But for a really effective full-body workout, I'll have to pull out my 
old "Thighs of Steel" and "Buns of Steel" videos to supplement my 
treadmill/Bowflex regimen"
      </i></blockquote>
<br />
You can read more of these reviews <a href="http://www.amazon.com/review/B001AS697O/?_encoding=UTF8&amp;showViewpoints=1&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957" target="_blank">here.</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="https://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=ur2&amp;o=1" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /><br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
So it seems that what you want from a home gym will largely determine whether or not you will be happy with a home gym like the Bowflex PR 1000. If you want to lift heavy weights and max out your strength and muscle gain, you would probably be happier with&nbsp; the Bowflex PR3000 or some other home gym with more capacity.<br />
<br />
On the other hand, if you want a economical home gym with a good variety of resistance exercises that can give you a good overall workout from head to toe, this may be the gym for you.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/4492444098437691579-7761134961194625631?l=home-exercise-equipment.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/OozldRfNDxVNjR3zMlImqhEEsZ4/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/OozldRfNDxVNjR3zMlImqhEEsZ4/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/OozldRfNDxVNjR3zMlImqhEEsZ4/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/OozldRfNDxVNjR3zMlImqhEEsZ4/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~4/JA5J2jxAW9Y" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
