    <item>
      <title>What Are Some Good Minimalist Running Shoes I Can Buy At A Reasonable Price?</title>
      <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~3/IDpli8fPy2c/what-are-some-good-minimalist-running.html</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 06 May 2012 17:41:01 GMT</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<br />
Albert asks,<b> " Tell me what my options are in a good pair of minimalist running shoes that are lightweight with good sole. I'm looking for a pair under $80. "</b><br />
<br />
We found some good options Albert. All are highly rated by those that already use them and with a bit of shopping, you should be able to meet your 80 dollar price target.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Wvku9SUK7oQ/T6asphsno6I/AAAAAAAABkk/tc-kqOT6O-c/s1600/Saucony+Mens+Hattori.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" height="125" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Wvku9SUK7oQ/T6asphsno6I/AAAAAAAABkk/tc-kqOT6O-c/s200/Saucony+Mens+Hattori.jpg" width="200" /></a>The <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004O2HFA8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B004O2HFA8">Saucony Men's Hattori Running Shoes</a> are good minimalist running shoes although not as nearly barefoot as the Vibrams Five Finger shoes. You'll still get the minimalist feel but with a thicker sole. <br />
<br />
Bill writes, "<i> ...I have two pairs of the Hattori, with nearly 130 miles between them, and
 for longest runs of 7-8 miles.  These are really good minimal cushioned
 shoes that fit the niche between traditional neutral cushioned trainers
 and BF shoes like Vibram Five Fingers (VFF).<br /><br />The Hattori is 
similar to Nike Free 3.0 in weight, flexibility and cushioning-- but 
with no heel-toe drop.  They have a slightly tighter fit than NF with 
the slipper-like construction."</i><br />
<br />
The Hattori is Saucony's lightest, most minimal shoe to date. The out-sole material is a very durable carbon rubber with exceptional traction. <br />
<br />
<table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="float: left; margin-right: 1em; text-align: left;"><tbody>
<tr><td style="text-align: center;"><img border="0" height="200" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-vm1XDwf4pOk/T6axrBauOPI/AAAAAAAABkw/tCbucObQTAY/s200/new+balance+mt+101.jpg" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width="200" /></td></tr>
<tr><td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;"><br /></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
The <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B003GXEG76/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B003GXEG76">New Balance Men's MT101 Trail Running Shoe</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B003GXEG76" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /> is another low profile running shoe that offers a bit of protection via the steel rock plate. The added protection is a great feature for many trail runners but true - ( read : hardcore ) - minimalist may not like it.<br />
<br />
One reviewer, ultramen, summed up his experience like this.<i>" I've ran more than 100ks with this pair, mostly on trails. These are very light and comfortable even in rough terrain.<br /><br />Compared
 to my old pairs, my feet never really felt battered after running on 
mt101's on trails, no heelstrikes nor overstriding. My feet are landing 
at the right, natural spots - the forefoot to midfoot.<br /><br />The design is wicked, I had never seen a shoe that imitates the color of a green beetle.</i><br />
<br />
<i>Anton and NB really nailed it with this one."</i><br />
<br />
John, who is new to trail running had this to say.<i> "Being new at trail running and the minimalist running style, I tried 
vibrams 5 fingers and the running sandle described in "Born To Run". I 
liked both of these but felt a little too unprotected.&nbsp;</i><br />
<br />
<i>The 101's solved 
all these issues and still felt very minimal. I have done some trail 
runs and speed workouts on the track and they performed great. Very 
light, feet felt very natural at ground strike and for the first time in
 any running shoe, I had no blisters from the very first run. Great 
product and am anxiously awaiting the "minimalist" shoe to come out in 
early 2011."</i><br />
<br />
If you are looking for shoes that feel almost like walking or running barefoot, consider the minimalist <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005NMZ3TI/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B005NMZ3TI">Vivobarefoot Men's Evo Running Shoes</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B005NMZ3TI" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" />.<br />
<br />
<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005NMZ3TI/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B005NMZ3TI" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;" target="_blank"><img border="0" height="200" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-zbYqW1lI_UI/T6a1ovi3HzI/AAAAAAAABk8/0Kotmv2GBUQ/s200/vivo+barefoot.jpg" width="200" /></a></div>
<i>&nbsp;Phil</i> calls them the best shoes he's ever had. <i>"I just ran for the first time in my new Terra Plana Evos.  These shoes 
are fantastic.  I ran for about a year in Nike Free 7.0 then a year in 
Nike Free 5.0.  Then I ordered the Nike Free Run+, Nike Free 3.0, and 
Terra Plana Evo.&nbsp;</i><br />
<br />
<i>The Run+ fit pretty good but because the tongue is not
 separate (it's called a sock) it was a little hard to get into.  But 
once in it did feel pretty good.  It has more cushion than the Nike 5.0 
so if you're into the barefoot running philosophy, then this is a bit of
 a step backward from the 5.0.  The Nike Free 3.0 was very narrow.  I 
returned it.  I wear a ten in most shoes and if I were to try the Nike 
Free 3.0 again I would probably try an 11.  I held the size 10 Nike Free
 3.0 and the size 10 Nike Free Run+ sole to sole and the 3.0 was 
noticably more narrow and slightly shorter.&nbsp;</i><br />
<br />
<i>With my wide foot I think 
I'll just pass on the Nike Free 3.0.  This is especially true now that I
 ran for the first time in my Terra Plana Evos.  This is a fantastic 
shoe.  It's very light.  It fit perfectly.  I felt like I was runing in 
socks.  It didn't feel like a shoe at all.  This is by far the best 
first try of any shoe I have ever tried.  It's like running in Vibran 
Five Fingers without the hastle of trying to get my rigid toes into the 
toe holes.  I highly recommend the Terra Plana Evo to anyone interested 
in barefoot running, especially if you have a wide foot and/or you don't
 like Five Fingers.&nbsp;</i><br />
<br />
<i>&nbsp;This shoe is really perfect.  I don't mean to 
discourage those with a narrow foot; I'm sure the laces will make it fit
 anyone.  My point is that for someone with a wide foot who has trouble 
with Nike and other shoes that tend to run narrow, this shoe is the one 
for you!  I love it!"</i><br />
<br />
<i>**** </i><br />
<br />
For more on shoes, check these out: <i></i><br />
<i><br /></i><br />
<a href="http://www.squidoo.com/workshop/asics-kinsei" target="_blank"><i>Asics Kensei</i></a><br />
<br />
<i><a href="http://www.squidoo.com/asics-cumulus" target="_blank">Gel Cumulus 13&nbsp;</a> </i><br />
<i><br /></i><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/4492444098437691579-5427512184195839254?l=home-exercise-equipment.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dShxiqDcho3855NkL9ED4mKNbo4/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dShxiqDcho3855NkL9ED4mKNbo4/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dShxiqDcho3855NkL9ED4mKNbo4/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dShxiqDcho3855NkL9ED4mKNbo4/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~4/IDpli8fPy2c" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
      <enclosure url="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/home-exercise-equipment-reviews-and-tips/Home_Exercise_Equipment_Reviews_And_Tips-What_Are_Some_Good_Minimalist_Running_Shoes_I_Can_Buy_At_A_Reasonable_Price.mp3" length="2494906" type="audio/mpeg" />
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>New Balance Men's MT20v1 Trail Minimus Shoe</title>
      <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~3/GdhvZD-fl48/new-balance-mens-mt20v1-trail-minimus.html</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 May 2012 23:25:33 GMT</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004KZP5AG/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B004KZP5AG">New Balance Men's MT20v1 Trail Minimus Shoes</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B004KZP5AG" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /> allow you to have a near barefoot running experience in a comfortable minimal running show with socks or without.

The Trail Minimus got high marks ( 4.4 out of 5 ) from the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/review/B004KZP5AG/?_encoding=UTF8&amp;showViewpoints=1&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957" target="_blank">customer reviews</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="https://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=ur2&amp;o=1" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /> we found at Amazon.<br />
<br />
<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
<a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ayfaqaxfd10/T6Bw4bW7VUI/AAAAAAAABkY/tjimrZRetQE/s1600/new+balance+mens+trail+minimus.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" height="320" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ayfaqaxfd10/T6Bw4bW7VUI/AAAAAAAABkY/tjimrZRetQE/s320/new+balance+mens+trail+minimus.jpg" width="271" /></a></div>
Let's take a look at some representative snippets, shall we?

<i>Angela</i> tells us her husband was ready to try something new after a couple of pairs of Nike Frees. While Hubby's original pair of 7.0 Frees " lasted for several years and were superb" the second pair was never comfortable and began deteriorating after several months. Thus the switch to New Balance Trail Minimus.

These shoes exceeded his expectations and were "easily the best pair of running shoes he has owned right out of the box."<br />
<br />
Angela tells us her husband like the lightweight yet sturdy design, saying the Vibram sole construction is top notch. The fit was accurate and the width was correct unlike other brands. These are the most comfortable shoes he has worn and the heel cup padding is particularly noteworthy. The performance is also great - the vibram sole is " Not too springy, and not too pliable, they provide a perfect balance between a barefoot feel and providing protection from sharp rocks and glass."

<i>&nbsp;</i><br />
<br />
<i>Jimi</i> had been using five finger shoes for the past year when he got a pair of Trail Minimus shoes. He calls the, ".. a major breakthrough in footwear". For one thing, these shoes are more "versatile stylistically". Jimi can wear these shoe with jeans or shorts without getting the stares a pair of five finger footwear might generate!

As you might expect, the New Balance Trail Minimus shoes offer more support.<br />
<br />
But Jimi finds them also less restrictive that five fingers " which kind of make my toes feel stiff due to the material separating them.' With plenty of room in the toe box Jimi has a more fuller range of motion for his toes. He's " ...been telling everyone I know to try these shoes. They are really THAT great. "

Click here to <a href="http://www.amazon.com/review/B004KZP5AG/?_encoding=UTF8&amp;showViewpoints=1&amp;tag=folthenewyory-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957" target="_blank">find out what everyone is saying</a><img alt="" border="0" height="1" src="https://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=folthenewyory-20&amp;l=ur2&amp;o=1" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;" width="1" /> about men's New Balance Trail Minimus shoes.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/4492444098437691579-827032949829207235?l=home-exercise-equipment.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iWYWvHKvKVpNEGSMhkYcJFHxHNM/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iWYWvHKvKVpNEGSMhkYcJFHxHNM/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iWYWvHKvKVpNEGSMhkYcJFHxHNM/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iWYWvHKvKVpNEGSMhkYcJFHxHNM/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~4/GdhvZD-fl48" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
