    <item>
      <title>Wondering Whether to Get Minimalist Running Shoe - Or Not?</title>
      <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~3/kcXMGtZw0AM/wondering-whether-to-get-minimalist.html</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 08 Apr 2012 17:26:31 GMT</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-JUaCLA-wCyg/T4HIususw4I/AAAAAAAABik/lkHVchHpvLk/s1600/Barefoot-Running-Woman.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" height="200" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-JUaCLA-wCyg/T4HIususw4I/AAAAAAAABik/lkHVchHpvLk/s200/Barefoot-Running-Woman.jpg" width="155" /></a></div>
Minimalist running shoes with less cushioning and lowered heels have become a popular alternative to the more traditional running shoes.<br />
<br />
Proponents of minimalist running consider it a more natural approach to running. They tell us that the minimalist style of running promotes running on the fore foot and mid-foot. Running this way leads to less injury that the heel strike landing that normal running shoes promote, they say.<br />
<br />
Proponents of minimalist running point out that this is not a fad. It is in line with the natural way men and women have ran since the dawn of time. Highly cushioned running shoes with a thick heel became popular starting in the 1970's. Minimalist claim these cushioned shoes cause a <a href="http://www.thepeacefulrunner.com/barefoot-running.html#axzz1rTCejfuY" target="_blank">high percentage of running related injuries</a>. <br />
<br />
