    <item>
      <title>Preventing Muscle Soreness - A Few Tips</title>
      <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~3/_0tcNETVBWs/preventing-muscle-soreness-few-tips.html</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Feb 2012 17:57:57 GMT</pubDate>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-uWuGWji5AfI/TyrJmTUaIDI/AAAAAAAABd8/lHET9djM1OM/s1600/lower%2Bback%2Bpain.jpg"><img style="float:right; margin:0 0 10px 10px;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 320px; height: 319px;" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-uWuGWji5AfI/TyrJmTUaIDI/AAAAAAAABd8/lHET9djM1OM/s320/lower%2Bback%2Bpain.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5704593537876238386" border="0" /></a><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Muscle soreness</span> suffered from exercise is something we would all like to prevent - or at least minimize.  And while it is no doubt true that at least a little soreness in the muscles we have been exercising is unavoidable, there are some easy things we can do to make that soreness less severe.<br /><br />If you are just starting out exercising - or significantly changing your exercise routine - progress slowly and gradually. Give yourself a couple of weeks to ease into a full workout schedule. I use this method whenever I commit to 13 weeks of <a href="http://teambeachbody.com/shop/-/shopping/P90X?referringRepId=38076">P90X</a>.<br /><br />I simply take two weeks before the formal program and go through some of the workouts - especially X Stretch and Yoga X. That way I'm not starting from scratch.<br /><br />And whenever you workout take 5 to 10 minutes to warm up and stretch your muscles. Taking a few minutes to cool down is just as important.<br /><br />A little massage - even self-massaging - of the muscle you have worked out can help with the soreness.<br /><br />While I resist taking muscle relaxers and even aspirin to help relax my muscles, I found a little topically applied Capsaicin can instantly take away any aches and pains. I asked my Doctor about it and he enthusiastically was in favor of it.<br /><br />If you do overdo it ( and we all do at times), don't make matters worse by trying to push through the pain. Back off a little bit from the heavy duty stuff and give your body the time it needs to repair and restore itself. You are not gaining anything by not allowing your body to recover.<br /><br />Preventing muscle soreness is usually just a common sense thing. Listen to your body and you will not go too far astray.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/4492444098437691579-8003755821624175575?l=home-exercise-equipment.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dvf_df10wmhtBQNNlCiTXcPqRgw/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dvf_df10wmhtBQNNlCiTXcPqRgw/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dvf_df10wmhtBQNNlCiTXcPqRgw/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/dvf_df10wmhtBQNNlCiTXcPqRgw/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/HomeExerciseEquipmentReviewsAndTips/~4/_0tcNETVBWs" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
      <enclosure url="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/home-exercise-equipment-reviews-and-tips/Home_Exercise_Equipment_Reviews_And_Tips-Preventing_Muscle_Soreness_-_A_Few_Tips.mp3" length="878328" type="audio/mpeg" />
